The 2001 economic assessment was based on the assumption that the section close to the border and the section leading through the Bohemian Central Mountains would go under traffic at the same time.
At the time of the examination it was obvious that the section through the Bohemian Central Mountains would not be opened at the original date.
This reduces the above-mentioned EIRR values.
As of 31 December 2005, the cost of both sections was €897 million excluding VAT, 27.4% higher than in the 2001 economic performance assessment.
In addition, there is a risk that section 0805 will have a different, more elaborate route, which would affect the economic viability of the project.
The economic assessment showed that the construction of both sections of the motorway is economically justified with a daily traffic volume of at least 18,000 cars per day in 2010. The forecast for 2008 had predicted 22,940 cars per day.
However, a study on diversion routes as an alternative to the missing section through the Bohemian Central Mountains assumes a traffic volume of 12,600 to 13,750 cars per day in 2007, and the project is below the economic limit.
A higher volume of traffic on the routes intended to replace the missing section with the Bohemian Central Mountains is most likely to result in congestion and thus increased external costs, which were not taken into account in the original economic assessment.
The aforementioned reduction in revenue and increase in costs means that the already low EIRR for the construction of the border section of the D 8 will not be achieved.
The construction of the border section of the D 8 is therefore uneconomical.
Cost increases also occurred in the construction of the A 17, as in the construction of the two aforementioned sections of the D 8.
In the context of the overall economic assessment for the Federal Transport Route Plan 1992, the Federal Ministry of Transport, responsible for transport, estimated investment costs of around €320 million.
As a result, it determined a benefit / cost ratio of 4.6.
In the meantime, costs have increased to around €670 million and the benefit / cost ratio has been reduced by more than half.
Regardless of the parallel tests with the NKÚ, the BRH had examined the economic viability of the planning and construction of the A17 motorway between 2003 and 2005.
He noted that the authority responsible for the approval called for an unnecessary landscape tunnel for the third section of the A 17.
During the course of the examination, the BRH succeeded in convincing the Federal Ministry and the Road Construction Administration of the superfluity of the landscape tunnel.
As a result, €10 million in construction costs and €150 000 in annual operating costs were avoided.
During the examination of the first section of the A 17, the BRH found that the construction measure was inadequately prepared.
The following example illustrates this:
During the planning phase, the road construction administration refrained from recording the condition of the rock on the surface of the Dölzschener Wand, as it was difficult to access.
It was only when the tunnel drive reached the wall that she picked up this.
It turned out that the rock was more weathered than was assumed in the tender.
Expensive measures such as anchorages, injections and stone-strike protection nets for around €3.3 million were necessary.
The road construction administration not only borne the costs of additional, already necessary services such as securing the Dölzschener Wand, but also for those that would not have been necessary in the event of proper construction preparation.
These include expenditure due to disturbed construction processes (€3.2 million), additional involvement of the propulsion team (€0.5 million) and increased wages and material prices due to the extension of construction time (€7 million).
This additional expenditure of around €10.7 million is not matched by any lasting added value.
The BRH took these and other measures as an opportunity to call on the Federal Ministry to better perceive the specialist supervision for large road construction measures that it is responsible for.
In this context, it should insist on the introduction of quality assurance systems by road construction authorities.
Benefits of cooperation for BRH and NKÚ The cooperation met the expectations of both auditors.
The BRH received insights into the planning, procurement and implementation of the construction of the border bridge.
Both auditors developed a database on bridge and tunnel prices, which will be helpful in future audits.
The NKÚ found that the most important structural parameters for bridges, tunnels and roadways of the D 8 are not different from those of the A 17.
The auditors of both auditors involved in the cooperation gathered valuable experience, which will be useful in future audits.
